<dl id="n53095o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53095o">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53095o"> 95(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shadow, <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53095o"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">TELEVISION TOPICS&mdash;Continued <p>HAVE you ever noticed when looking at television pictures a sort of <mark>shadow</mark> or ghost outline around a sharp-edge dark object on a light background? At first thought it might appear that this was due to some maladjustment in the receiver or sorne light effect at the transmitter.</p> <small> <a name="PWT25dec37" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#PWT25dec37"><cite title="source">Populary Wireless and Television Times</cite></a> (25 December 1937) 394a</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The use of silhouette or shadowgraph pictures, and of stills, was common during the early demonstrations of television given in the 1920s by J.C. Baird in England. Occasionally, a second, displaced, fainter ghost image appeared on the screen. </mm> </dd></dl>
